SIMPLE: mortise
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mortise
<hw>Mor"tise</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>mortaise</ets>; cf. Sp. <ets>mortaja</ets>, Ar. <ets>murtazz</ets>
fixed, or W. <ets>mortais</ets>, Ir. <ets>mortis</ets>,
<ets>moirtis</ets>, Gael. <ets>moirteis</ets>.]</ety> <def>A cavity cut
into a piece of timber, or other material, to receive something (as the
end of another piece) made to fit it, and called a
<inv>tenon</inv>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mortise and tenon</b></col> <fld>(Carp.)</fld>, <cd>made
with a mortise and tenon; joined or united by means of a mortise and
tenon; -- used adjectively.</cd> -- <col><b>Mortise joint</b></col>,
<cd>a joint made by a mortise and tenon.</cd> -- <col><b>Mortise
lock</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Lock</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mortise
wheel</b></col>, <cd>a cast-iron wheel, with wooden clogs inserted in
mortises on its face or edge; -- also called <altname>mortise
gear</altname>, and <altname>core gear</altname>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortise</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mortise
<hw>Mor"tise</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Mortised</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Mortising</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cut or make a
mortise in.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To join or fasten by a tenon and mortise; <as>as, to
<ex>mortise</ex> a beam into a post, or a joist into a
girder</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortling</ent>⟦br⟧
